<div id="review_179512014" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/179512014" />
    <a title="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2190636-joselito-honestly-and-brilliantly"><img alt="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1349701607p2/2190636.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/179512014?book_show_action=true">Jun 25, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly" href="/user/show/2190636-joselito-honestly-and-brilliantly">Joselito Honestly and Brilliantly</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780061353468" href="/book/show/6581343-the-kindly-ones">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer179512014" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17593950144675086464">You&apos;re given a free trip to Europe, time-travelling back to world war two. Your vehicle is one of the two characters you are free to choose from: one, a Jew who hid for many months, was caught by the Germans, placed in a concentration camp, then died before the war was over; the other a Nazi officer who had been everywhere, practically met everyone of consequence in the German military, and survived the war. You will be like the character&apos;s shadow. You will be with him wherever he goes, 24/7. Yo</span>
  <span id="freeText17593950144675086464" style="display:none">You're given a free trip to Europe, time-travelling back to world war two. Your vehicle is one of the two characters you are free to choose from: one, a Jew who hid for many months, was caught by the Germans, placed in a concentration camp, then died before the war was over; the other a Nazi officer who had been everywhere, practically met everyone of consequence in the German military, and survived the war. You will be like the character's shadow. You will be with him wherever he goes, 24/7. You will see, hear and experience everything within the ambit of his senses. You will suffer no harm, but neither can you change anything that had happened. <br /><br />Which character will you choose to hitch a ride with? <br /><br />Read this book and you'll be the shadow of Sturmbannfuhrer Maximilian Aue (later promoted to Obersturmbannfuhrer, the rank equivalent to the Lieutenent-Colonel of the American army), an officer in the SS in an almost perpetual state of throwing up and diarrhea. He is a lawyer, an expert in constitutional law, but prefers to call himself a jurist, thus "Dr. Aue," before the war. He is also gay, yet has an infantile, obsessive and unbreakable incestuous bond with is only sibling, his twin sister. With him, you'll see Europe at war, criss-crossing Germany, Poland, France, Russia, etc. He was even there at Stalingrad, surviving the siege a false hero. Through this guy you'll see the glory of Nazi Germany at its mightiest and the horrors of the concentration camps it created. You'll have close contacts with the architects of the Holocaust, guys like Heinrich Himmler, Adolf Eichmann and even Hitler himself whose nose Aue manages to bite, and hear them discuss philosophy, music and their inmates' diet. The common holocaust literature is written from the Jews' point of view. Here, you'll meet the SUFFERING German officers and soldiers, driven to savagery, brutality and, sometimes, insanity because they are forced to do things "for Germany" which deep inside their hearts they know are morally reprehensible. Like they are forced to gas their own parents, children or friends, they cannot disobey, these people had become Germany's enemies, so they instead vent their anger upon these unfortunate, innocent victims, blaming them FOR BEING THERE. <br /><br />I could have easily disliked this book because of the novel written in it. The novel's length alone makes it unattractive to one like me whose TBR list grows longer everytime I visit a bookstore (which is everyday). The paragraphs are long; Aue sounds ridiculous in his supposedly dramatic moments; those improbable coincidences in an otherwise historically-accurate events; unmemorable prose, pretentious declamations and, again, Aue's fountains of shit and vomit which you can practically smell in every page. <br /><br />But who cares? I had gone into an adventure, went to hell and now I'm back. Which novel you've read can boast of accomplishing something like this for its readers? Thus, four stars and to hell with its critics!</span>
  <a data-text-id="17593950144675086464" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


