  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_49516807" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/49516807" />
    <a title="Denis" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1729623-denis"><img alt="Denis" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1227151520p2/1729623.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/49516807?book_show_action=true">Mar 16, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Denis" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Denis" href="/user/show/1729623-denis">Denis</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer49516807" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3535941095840261907">I read this book in its French original version - which is important, because many American reviews are harsh with the author&apos;s writing style, and that may be due to the translation: Littell&apos;s French is actually quite beautiful - he writes in a direct, precise, elegantly classic way, and it does perfectly serve his story as well as it fits the narrator&apos;s voice. This story is, of course, at the center of the huge controversy the novel is creating - a controversy that has exploded in every country</span>
  <span id="freeText3535941095840261907" style="display:none">I read this book in its French original version - which is important, because many American reviews are harsh with the author's writing style, and that may be due to the translation: Littell's French is actually quite beautiful - he writes in a direct, precise, elegantly classic way, and it does perfectly serve his story as well as it fits the narrator's voice. This story is, of course, at the center of the huge controversy the novel is creating - a controversy that has exploded in every country where the book has been published, including in France, although the book won two of the most prestigious French literary prizes, and became a gigantic best-seller. Let's put it this way: The Kindly Ones is an extraordinary book, but it's also not without some flaws, and it is sometimes extremely difficult to read because of its subject matter. The Holocaust, and the horrors perpetrated by the Nazis, will always remain controversial material for any book of fiction - and that's understandable. Littell, though, has done the unthinkable: he's put himself into the skin of a member of the SS, who narrates his experiences through WWII - sparing us no details of the horrendous actions the Nazis did in Ukraine or in the camps, for example, but also taking us to the siege of Stalingrad, one of the darkest hour of WWII, or to the apocalyptic fall of Germany, and, more precisely, Berlin. All those pages are so vividly written, with such an incredible and indelible sense of detail, that the reader feels he's right there, where the action is taking place. Many people have been offended by those pages - mostly the ones describing the massacres of the Jews. But the thing is, those pages describe what happened, and how it happened - not with the intellectual distance of the historian, but through the eyes of a willing participant who obliges the reader to look, and to smell, and to walk among the bodies, and not to turn away. Yes, it's hell on Earth. But these events are not fiction. The horror was real - and Littell wants us to feel it in every way. His amazing talent is to write about all this as if he had been there, at the time. It's certainly very disturbing - but Littell never excuses his anti-hero, nor does he in any way condone his actions. The author's other incredible achievement is the way he describes how the Nazi machine worked during the war: the structure in power was an amazingly complex political machine, yet Littell seems to know all there is to know about it, and he takes the reader inside that world like no other writer has done it. His novel is massive: 900 pages, and it clearly hopes to be on the level of Grossman's masterpiece Life and Fate. It comes close. I read it fast. Despite the myriads of names, actions, scenes, and the intricate details of the war events that follow each other in an unstoppable flow (there are no chapters), it never is an incomprehensible book. On the contrary. Now, of course, the question is: what has Littell tried to achieve? Everybody has an opinion on the matter. I personally believe that he has tried to show us how what happened could happen, and what kind of men (sometimes intelligent, educated, sophisticated men) did what they did. What better way to do that but to let a Nazi speak? Littell's narrator believes in Nazism, is anti-semitic, participates to the holocaust: through him, we have a glimpse of how some people can justify their actions to themselves, feel a certain way about another group of human beings, and be an active part of a repressive system. As for the capacity of violence, obviously Littell thinks that everybody has it in itself: it's not a very new idea, but he demonstrates its reality with startling effects. One problem is that the main character, Aue,happens to be a very tortured man, whose past is littered with dark secrets, and who is a psychopath: I wonder if the book would not have been stronger if Aue had been a much more ordinary man. Most Germans were. When it comes to the parts of the story that are pure fiction (Aue's past, his loves, etc), Littell's is on more shaky grounds, and is not as in control of his narration as he is when he writes about the war. He's even boring and repetitive when he goes on and on about his character's sexual fantasies. The last 100 pages suffer from those flaws. But overall, The Kindly Ones is an extremely impressive achievement, which shows us the "bowels" of the Nazi party (much more than the bowels of Nazi Germany - there is a difference) like nobody else has done it before - actually, like nobody else has ever dared doing it. It is shocking, often disgusting, and you'll have nightmares. But it is an important book. I don't think, unlike some critics, that it's an unhealthy, perverse, gross, sick novel. Quite the contrary. The tour of hell it obliges us to take is a tour of humankind at its worse, and it's essential, in our days and age, to have the courage to face what supposedly civilized people can do. Yes, the events that Littell writes about are repulsive and unbelievably horrific. But he has not invented them. He has just found a way (reprehensible, according to some) to bring us as close as possible to them, and to one of the most nightmarish moment of our History, not because he wants us to take pleasure in reading about it all (and unless you're a sick person, you won't), but to make us think. And, indeed, this book made me think like few books have. It is a very unique novel. I wouldn't recommend it to everybody, for obvious reasons. But I do believe it'll remain one of the great, even if always controversial, novels of our era.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3535941095840261907" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


