  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1397205519" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1397205519" />
    <a title="Lobstergirl" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1910836-lobstergirl"><img alt="Lobstergirl" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1380256801p2/1910836.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1397205519?book_show_action=true">Sep 20, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lobstergirl" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lobstergirl" href="/user/show/1910836-lobstergirl">Lobstergirl</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1910836-lobstergirl?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1397205519" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8307449052952947344"><br/>In some ways this was like a German <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28676.American_Psycho' title='American Psycho by Bret Easton Ellis' rel='nofollow noopener'>American Psycho</a>, although that work was a pure satire, a comic novel, not historical fiction, and this (at least, I think) isn’t intended to be satire. But if you posit that both novels take a stereotypical “worst example” of each country’s upper middle class young male – a slick Wall Street misogynist on one hand and a cultivated, intelligent, ruthless SS officer on the other - and push them to the limits of sociopathy and beyond, it’s an interesting comparis</span>
  <span id="freeText8307449052952947344" style="display:none"><br />In some ways this was like a German <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28676.American_Psycho" title="American Psycho by Bret Easton Ellis" rel="nofollow noopener">American Psycho</a>, although that work was a pure satire, a comic novel, not historical fiction, and this (at least, I think) isn’t intended to be satire. But if you posit that both novels take a stereotypical “worst example” of each country’s upper middle class young male – a slick Wall Street misogynist on one hand and a cultivated, intelligent, ruthless SS officer on the other - and push them to the limits of sociopathy and beyond, it’s an interesting comparison.<br /><br />Most of Littell’s novel is straight-up historical fiction, as his first person narrator Max Aue travels to Poland, Belarus, Ukraine and the Caucasus to observe the liquidation of local Jewish populations, the battle of Stalingrad, Auschwitz, late-war Berlin with Himmler, Speer and Eichmann, and the Red Army’s final westward advance. Over this he lays the disturbed personality of Aue, a man given to incest with his twin sister, matricide, vivid hallucinations, tree-fucking, and lots and lots of vomiting and diarrhea, which I took to be both visceral representations of the hell the Nazis visited upon their victims, and unconscious “sympathy” suffering mirroring the same, in the manner of a pregnant woman’s husband experiencing morning sickness. I could tell in many places where Littell and I had probably read the same historical sources, and I suspect one of those is Klaus Theweleit’s <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/163117.Male_Fantasies_Volume_1_Women__Floods__Bodies__History" title="Male Fantasies Volume 1 Women, Floods, Bodies, History by Klaus Theweleit" rel="nofollow noopener">Male Fantasies: Volume 1: Women, Floods, Bodies, History</a>, a book that examined the sexual and scatological perversions of the <i>Freikorps</i>.<br /><br />We see glimmers in Aue of what should not be mistaken for humanity: a concern that Jews in the death camps should be treated better and that the inmates being evacuated from Auschwitz need shoes and food is not altruism, but practicality – there’s an immense manpower shortage in Germany, and the Jews are needed for efficient slave labor. But as the novel and the war wind down, whatever mechanisms Aue has been using to keep from sliding into overt sociopathy vanish, and we see him kill not just enemies but allies, an elderly Prussian Junker who is playing Bach on a church organ, and finally <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[his best friend Thomas <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>.<br /><br />Toward the war’s end life in the Reich, even for those considered the master race, got less and less valuable. German deserters were strung up on lampposts with wild abandon, even with the manpower shortage. People were shot by their superiors for the most minuscule reasons. Littell creates a small nightmare scenario in the form of a band of Lord-of-the-Flies type boys and girls who beat Aue’s driver to death, and imitate the behavior of both the German and Russian soldiers they’ve seen, by raping the girls in their group publicly. I don’t know if this particular scene was based on historical events or fabricated, but given that it involved children, it was one of the novel’s more horrifying set-pieces.<br /><br />I’m not sure what Littell was trying to do with his novel. As storytelling, as historical fiction, there’s certainly nothing wrong with it, although I did find a sentence that went on for three and a half pages. The classic histories and biographies of the Third Reich, all together, do a better job. Obviously you don’t write a thousand page novel (if it had paragraph breaks it would probably be 1,200) with a subject which has been covered so thoroughly by the historians unless you plan to shed some new light on, explore some new aspect of, say something unique and uniquely literary about these events and these people. What enlightenment was delivered here, I can’t say.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="8307449052952947344" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review1397205519">
  <td colspan="2">
    <div class="updateActionLinks">
