<div id="review_13508096" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/13508096" />
    <a title="Marianne" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/831329-marianne"><img alt="Marianne" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/13508096?book_show_action=true">Jan 25, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marianne" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marianne" href="/user/show/831329-marianne">Marianne</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9782070780976" href="/book/show/241524.Les_Bienveillantes">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer13508096" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9842419309235360591">Pages and pages of gore, entrails, decapitations, burnings, burials, shootings, burnings.... as if we didn&apos;t know that certain &quot;people&quot; had done these things. I do not and will never understand why this was a Prix Goncourt. It should have been Prix du Mauvais Gout.<br/><br/>Update: For reasons that escape me,I took a second try a this book and managed to get through the 903 pages. Extremely contrived plot where somehow a SS officer(who, of course, appreciates great literature, classical music and fine win</span>
  <span id="freeText9842419309235360591" style="display:none">Pages and pages of gore, entrails, decapitations, burnings, burials, shootings, burnings.... as if we didn't know that certain "people" had done these things. I do not and will never understand why this was a Prix Goncourt. It should have been Prix du Mauvais Gout.<br /><br />Update: For reasons that escape me,I took a second try a this book and managed to get through the 903 pages. Extremely contrived plot where somehow a SS officer(who, of course, appreciates great literature, classical music and fine wines) is located at the execution sites in Ukraine, Stalingrad, Auschwitz, Berlin and even the Bunker a few days before the end, meets Borman, Eichman, Himmler, Speer, Höss, Mengele, etal., and then survives to continue his malevolent life by writing endless pages. There was really nothing new, alas, except adding in various extraneous episodes of incest, family killings, and sex acts with various objects. Very difficult to follow the hundred of names and occupations mentioned. Since the author is apparently not acquainted with the use of paragraphs, conversations are doubly confusing as one is never sure who the speaker is. As someone knowledgeable about WW2, this was not a book that sheds any new light on the facts or psychology of the Nazis.</span>
