<div id="review_2552248883" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2552248883" />
    <a title="Tarun" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27099043-tarun"><img alt="Tarun" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1567670586p2/27099043.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2552248883?book_show_action=true">May 04, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tarun" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tarun" href="/user/show/27099043-tarun">Tarun</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780099513148" href="/book/show/7841951-the-kindly-ones">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2552248883" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18194889170949919371">This is a disturbing book that comes clean and makes it very clear at the beginning that it’s going to be full of VERY unpleasant things. So the first step you take towards it (out of morbid curiosity perhaps) in fact leads you down a slippery, vertiginous slope that drops right into an abyss. There’s no turning around or going back! This gaping, inescapable chasm is populated by a bewildering cast of characters who are in a state of free fall themselves. You stare at them and wonder : Did they </span>
  <span id="freeText18194889170949919371" style="display:none">This is a disturbing book that comes clean and makes it very clear at the beginning that it’s going to be full of VERY unpleasant things. So the first step you take towards it (out of morbid curiosity perhaps) in fact leads you down a slippery, vertiginous slope that drops right into an abyss. There’s no turning around or going back! This gaping, inescapable chasm is populated by a bewildering cast of characters who are in a state of free fall themselves. You stare at them and wonder : Did they choose this? Or was it fate? <br /><br />Dr. Max Aue, the protagonist, guides the readers on their journey to the bottom of this sunless sea. Europe’s engulfed by war and our ‘guide’ is presented to us as a well-oiled cog in the machinery that efficiently churns out death and destruction in service of some of the most nefarious goals known to mankind. Aue is cultivated, intelligent, and young. He is pursued by the Furies wherever he goes on his nasty missions. He is tortured by visions. He is scarred by the terrible events he witnesses/participates in. He carries a profoundly evil streak deep within the folds of his existence.<br /><br />Aue commits his experiences to writing in a straightforward, cold, unflinching manner. The nastiest episodes of destruction and cruelty he describes lucidly, without much sentimentality. But he also has these intense visions that bring him to his knees, and make him lose himself in the miasmal labyrinths of his tormented past.<br /><br />The dehumanization that Aue and his ilk inflict upon their hapless victims also chips away at the humanity of the perpetrators themselves, and eventually disfigures them beyond recognition. <br /><br />Aue reminded me a lot of Celine’s frightful ‘anti-heros’, and this is what he had to say towards the end of the book :<br /><blockquote><br />Maybe, instead of my unwholesome, abstruse reflections, you would rather have anecdotes, spicy little stories...if I’m putting myself to so much trouble, it’s not to make you happy, I will willingly admit, it’s above all for my own mental hygiene, like when you’ve eaten too much, at some point you have to evacuate the waste, whether or not it smells nice, you don’t always have a choice; but here, you have an irrevocable power, that of closing this book and throwing it in the rubbish, a final recourse against which I am powerless, so I don’t see why I should wear kid gloves.<br /></blockquote><br />Be forewarned that the book has graphic scenes of death, bodily functions, and torture. I have no idea why I pick up such macabre books sometimes! <br />Phew!</span>
  <a data-text-id="18194889170949919371" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


