  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1175145954" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1175145954" />
    <a title="Bill Kupersmith" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12460952-bill-kupersmith"><img alt="Bill Kupersmith" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1428792100p2/12460952.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1175145954?book_show_action=true">Jan 20, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bill Kupersmith" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bill Kupersmith" href="/user/show/12460952-bill-kupersmith">Bill Kupersmith</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12460952-bill-kupersmith?shelf=five-stars-in-2015">five-stars-in-2015</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1175145954" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12318442532141861364">One day Les Bienveillantes will be “canonized” as a major literary classic &amp; form the subject of numerous graduate theses - had it been published 50 years ago I’d now be working hard on my French. I expect its failure to gain popularity in its American version as The Kindly Ones was due to reviewers’ fears that it would appeal to the sorts who collect phony SS memorabilia. They needn’t have worried: SS-Strumbahnführer Max Aue would scarcely inspire the kind of teenager who’s likely to show up @ </span>
  <span id="freeText12318442532141861364" style="display:none">One day Les Bienveillantes will be “canonized” as a major literary classic &amp; form the subject of numerous graduate theses - had it been published 50 years ago I’d now be working hard on my French. I expect its failure to gain popularity in its American version as The Kindly Ones was due to reviewers’ fears that it would appeal to the sorts who collect phony SS memorabilia. They needn’t have worried: SS-Strumbahnführer Max Aue would scarcely inspire the kind of teenager who’s likely to show up @ high school with what journalists misleadingly label “an assault rifle” (appropriately a term coined by Hitler himself!). Aue’s true lineage is derived from Aeschylus, Dante (we descend in narrowing circles, ending in Hitler's bunker), &amp; early 19th-century Romanticism - like Lord Byron, he’s in love with his sister.<br /><br />As with Orestes, he hates his mother &amp; her current husband &amp; idolizes his absent father, whom he discovers to have been a brutal Freikorps officer in Courland. When they found out about the sexual relationship with his twin sister, Max’s mother &amp; stepfather pack the teenaged Max off to a French Catholic boarding school where he acquires perfect French, a solid background in ancient Greek, &amp; a traumatic history of sexual abuse &amp; brutality that leaves him utterly bereft of any moral or spiritual values or beliefs or any capacity for loving relationships. Aside from his masturbatory fantasies involving his sister, Max’s principal sexual outlet is provided by brief encounters with men. In the course of the book he’s offered the love of a widow whom he treats with barely disguised contempt. In short, Max is a perfect candidate to join the Nazis. Insofar as he believes in anything @ all, Max is a through-going social Darwinist. Really his only relationship is with the SS itself. He is a total sycophant - it’s grimly funny to hear him constantly parroting “Yes, mein Reichsführer” @ Himmler. <br /><br />Littell presents the real historical characters brilliantly. His take on Eichmann was new to me - neither the raving anti-semitic murderer nor the banal bureaucrat, but a conscientious officer of limited imagination: sort of like a professional exterminator but of people. The fictitious characters (including the only real friends Max makes, a professor of linguistics &amp; a pathologist) are well-drawn too. Dr. Mandelbrod, with his bevy of blonde Valkyries (more myth stuff I expect) in Nazi uniforms, looks &amp; talks like some villain in a James Bond novel, but given the sheer insanity of Hitler’s court, I only knew he was fictitious because I’d never read about him before.<br /><br />I am most grateful to my Goodreads (&amp; real life) friend Sara for recommending this one, tho’ @ this stage in my life I could scarcely get through this monster except as a traveling audio book. I’ve long wanted to add a real believing Nazi to my literary experience, &amp; Aue fits that appalling bill perfectly. Whether this book is a classic will be determined by posterity, but I expect that it will always have readers.<br /><br />Generally I found both the translation &amp; the audio version quite agreeable &amp; am delighted to add enculé to my vocabulary to shout when some fellow motorist does a 180 in front of my car to snare the parking space that I was eyeing. But both are a little too American. I would imagine that a cultivated European who speaks perfect German &amp; French should be translated &amp; read in the kind of English you sometimes hear a very well-educated French or German speaker use - it’s identifiable as foreign only because it is too perfect for any native English-speaker, without any trace of a regional accent. Such a speaker would never suppose the past tense of “dive” was “dove”! As for the audio reader, whenever he impersonated the two Berlin detectives (who are the Eumenides of the book’s title), he dropped into his own imitation of Peter Falk performing Detective Colombo. I’d have preferred Bogart!</span>
  <a data-text-id="12318442532141861364" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

